    <item>
      <title>What Is Hermitian</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/what-is-hermitian/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 04 Mar 2025 06:19:57 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/what-is-hermitian/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;What is Hermitian?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_matrix&#34;&gt;Hermitian matrix&lt;/a&gt; is a complex square matrix that is equal to its own conjugate transpose.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is a conjugate transpose?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugate_transpose&#34;&gt;conjugate transpose&lt;/a&gt;, or adjoint matrix, is the matrix obtained by transposing &lt;em&gt;A&lt;/em&gt; and applying complex conjugation on each entry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is complex conjugation?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In mathematics, the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_conjugate&#34;&gt;complex conjugate&lt;/a&gt; of a complex number is the number with an equal real part and an imaginary part equal in magnitude but opposite in sign. Complex conjugates can be illustrated via an Argand diagram.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
